<HEADLINE>
<P>
1990 CENSUS QUESTIONS 
</P>
</HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
I thoroughly enjoyed Frank Clifford's overview of the 1990 census (front page, 
March 24) but was struck by the article's conclusion. Clifford writes: "One 
question on the census long form speaks volumes about old habits at the Census 
Bureau. 
</P>
<P>
In an age of spas and Jacuzzis and basement lap pools, the census form still 
wants to know if you have indoor plumbing." 
</P>
<P>
The need to include that particular question actually speaks more about the 
growing disparity between the rich and the poor during the 1980s than it does 
about the bureau's old habits. 
</P>
<P>
The 1990 census will generate a wealth of data, including information on the 
state of the impoverished in our society (despite the inevitable undercount of 
this population). The lack of indoor plumbing is common in areas such as rural 
Texas. Hopefully, this same information will encourage policy-makers to correct 
this situation, making the question obsolete by the time census 2000 rolls 
around. 
</P>
<P>
ARTURO VARGAS 
</P>
<P>
National Census Program Director 
</P>
<P>
Mexican American Legal Defense and Educational Fund 
</P>
<P>
Los Angeles 
</P>
</TEXT>
