<P>
WORLD; 
</P>
<P>
TENS OF THOUSANDS OF SOVIET GEORGIANS MARK SLAYING OF 19 
</P>
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
<P>
From Times Wire Services 
</P>
</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>
<P>
TBILISI, Soviet Union 
</P>
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
Tens of thousands of Soviet Georgians rallied in Tbilisi today on the 
anniversary of the slaying of 19 pro-independence protesters by Soviet forces, 
and burned the region's military chief in effigy. 
</P>
<P>
There was a partial re-enactment of last year's 4 a.m. assault, when troops 
armed with shotguns, shovels and toxic gas charged onto Rustaveli Boulevard in 
the Georgian capital. 
</P>
<P>
Radio stations broadcast the sound of rumbling tanks and ringing bells. 
</P>
<P>
From midnight Sunday through early today, people carrying flowers and candles 
thronged the boulevard. About 100,000 Georgians stood with raised fists for a 
silent moment to honor the dead. 
</P>
<P>
Later, demonstrators burned an effigy of Col. Gen. I. N. Rodionov, regional 
military commander, in front of the city's Government House, which overlooks 
the broad square where Soviet troops moved in. 
</P>
<P>
Nineteen people died in the clash a year ago, and another was killed by troops 
in a separate incident. Thousands suffered ailments from the gas. 
</P>
<P>
The assault caused a nationwide furor, raised doubts about President Mikhail S. 
Gorbachev's proclaimed policy of not using troops to stifle dissent and brought 
many Georgians into the battle for independence. 
</P>
<P>
The memorial protest Sunday and today had more an air of defiance than of 
mourning. Most speakers spoke of the impetus the deaths gave the republic's 
burgeoning independence movement. 
</P>
</TEXT>
